---
import Layout from '../../layouts/Layout.astro';
import { products } from '../../data/products';
import type { Product } from '../../data/products';

const slugOrder = ['google-nest-protect-battery', 'kidde-hardwired-wifi-smoke-detector', 'kidde-smart-smoke-co'];
const picks = slugOrder.map(slug => products.find(p => p.slug === slug)!).filter(Boolean) as Product[];
const topPick = picks[0];
---

<Layout
  title="Best Smart Smoke Detector (2026): Nest Protect vs Kidde Hardwired vs Kidde Smart"
  description="Smart smoke and CO detectors compared: Nest Protect, Kidde Smart Hardwired with Air Quality Monitor, and Kidde Smart. Which keeps your home safest and fits your ecosystem?"
>
  <div class="bg-amber-50 border-b border-amber-100">
    <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 py-2 text-xs text-amber-800 text-center">
      This site earns commissions from purchases made through our links at no extra cost to you.
    </div>
  </div>

  <article class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 py-12">

    <nav class="text-xs text-gray-400 mb-6">
      <a href="/" class="hover:text-green-700">Home</a>
      <span class="mx-2">›</span>
      <a href="/smart-home" class="hover:text-green-700">Smart Home</a>
      <span class="mx-2">›</span>
      Best Smart Smoke Detector
    </nav>

    <h1 class="text-3xl sm:text-4xl font-bold text-gray-900 mb-3 leading-tight">
      Best Smart Smoke Detector (2026)
    </h1>
    <p class="text-sm text-gray-400 mb-8">Last updated: April 2026 · 3 detectors compared</p>

    <p class="text-lg text-gray-700 mb-4 leading-relaxed">
      A smart smoke detector does everything a standard one does — but adds phone alerts when you're away, tells you which room the problem is in, and integrates with the rest of your smart home to take action automatically when triggered.
    </p>
    <p class="text-lg text-gray-700 mb-8 leading-relaxed">
      The three picks below represent the premium smart detector (Nest Protect), the best hardwired option with air quality monitoring (Kidde Smart Hardwired), and the most affordable battery-powered smart + CO combo (Kidde Smart). All detect both smoke and carbon monoxide — because CO is invisible and odorless, and every home should have combined coverage.
    </p>

    <div class="bg-red-50 border border-red-200 rounded-2xl p-5 mb-10">
      <p class="font-semibold text-gray-900 mb-2 text-sm">Why carbon monoxide detection matters as much as smoke</p>
      <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 leading-relaxed">Carbon monoxide kills approximately 400 people in the United States annually and injures thousands more. CO is produced by any combustion source: gas furnaces, water heaters, fireplaces, attached garages, and generators. It has no color or smell. Standard smoke detectors don't detect it. The NFPA recommends a combination smoke + CO detector on every level of your home and outside each sleeping area. All three picks on this page combine both in one unit.</p>
    </div>

    <!-- Top Pick Box -->
    <div class="bg-green-50 border border-green-200 rounded-2xl p-6 mb-10">
      <p class="text-xs font-semibold text-green-700 uppercase tracking-widest mb-3">Our Top Pick</p>
      <div class="flex flex-col sm:flex-row sm:items-center justify-between gap-4">
        <div>
          <h2 class="text-xl font-bold text-gray-900 mb-1">{topPick.name}</h2>
          <p class="text-gray-600 text-sm mb-2">{topPick.tagline}</p>
          <p class="text-2xl font-bold text-green-700">${topPick.price}</p>
        </div>
        <a
          href={topPick.affiliateUrl}
          target="_blank"
          rel="nofollow noopener"
          class="inline-block bg-green-700 text-white px-6 py-3 rounded-lg font-semibold text-sm hover:bg-green-800 transition-colors whitespace-nowrap text-center"
        >
          Check Price on Amazon →
        </a>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- Comparison Table -->
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mb-4">Quick Comparison</h2>
    <div class="overflow-x-auto mb-12 rounded-xl border border-gray-100">
      <table class="w-full text-sm">
        <thead>
          <tr class="bg-gray-50 border-b border-gray-200">
            <th class="text-left p-3 font-semibold text-gray-700">Detector</th>
            <th class="text-left p-3 font-semibold text-gray-700">Price</th>
            <th class="text-left p-3 font-semibold text-gray-700">Detects</th>
            <th class="text-left p-3 font-semibold text-gray-700">Power</th>
            <th class="text-left p-3 font-semibold text-gray-700">Ecosystem</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          {picks.map((p, i) => (
            <tr class={`border-b border-gray-100 ${i === 0 ? 'bg-green-50' : 'hover:bg-gray-50'}`}>
              <td class="p-3">
                <a href={`#${p.slug}`} class="font-medium text-gray-900 hover:text-green-700">{p.name}</a>
                {i === 0 && <span class="ml-2 text-xs bg-green-100 text-green-700 px-2 py-0.5 rounded-full font-medium">Top Pick</span>}
              </td>
              <td class="p-3 font-medium">${p.price}</td>
              <td class="p-3">{p.specs['Detects']}</td>
              <td class="p-3">{p.specs['Power']}</td>
              <td class="p-3">{p.specs['Smart Platforms']}</td>
            </tr>
          ))}
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>

    <!-- Individual Reviews -->
    {picks.map((product, i) => (
      <section id={product.slug} class="mb-16 scroll-mt-20">
        <div class="border-t border-gray-100 pt-10 mb-6">
          <p class="text-xs font-semibold text-green-700 uppercase tracking-widest mb-2">
            {i === 0 ? '🏆 Best Smart Smoke Detector' : i === 1 ? '🥈 Best Hardwired Smart Alarm with Air Quality Monitor' : '🥉 Best Budget Smart Smoke + CO Detector'}
          </p>
          <div class="flex flex-col sm:flex-row sm:items-start justify-between gap-4">
            <div>
              <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mb-1">{product.name}</h2>
              <p class="text-gray-500 text-sm">${product.price} &nbsp;·&nbsp; ⭐ {product.rating}/5</p>
            </div>
            <a
              href={product.affiliateUrl}
              target="_blank"
              rel="nofollow noopener"
              class="inline-block bg-green-700 text-white px-5 py-2.5 rounded-lg font-semibold text-sm hover:bg-green-800 transition-colors whitespace-nowrap"
            >
              Check on Amazon →
            </a>
          </div>
        </div>

        <p class="text-gray-700 mb-6 leading-relaxed">{product.tagline}</p>

        <div class="bg-gray-50 rounded-xl p-4 mb-6">
          <p class="text-xs font-semibold text-gray-400 uppercase tracking-widest mb-3">Key Specs</p>
          <div class="grid sm:grid-cols-2 gap-x-8">
            {Object.entries(product.specs).map(([key, val]) => (
              <div class="flex justify-between py-1.5 border-b border-gray-100 last:border-0">
                <span class="text-gray-500 text-sm">{key}</span>
                <span class="font-medium text-gray-900 text-sm">{val}</span>
              </div>
            ))}
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="grid sm:grid-cols-2 gap-4 mb-6">
          <div class="bg-green-50 rounded-xl p-4">
            <p class="font-semibold text-gray-900 mb-3 text-sm">Pros</p>
            <ul class="space-y-2">
              {product.pros.map(pro => (
                <li class="text-sm text-gray-700 flex gap-2">
                  <span class="text-green-600 flex-shrink-0 mt-0.5">✓</span>
                  {pro}
                </li>
              ))}
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="bg-red-50 rounded-xl p-4">
            <p class="font-semibold text-gray-900 mb-3 text-sm">Cons</p>
            <ul class="space-y-2">
              {product.cons.map(con => (
                <li class="text-sm text-gray-700 flex gap-2">
                  <span class="text-red-500 flex-shrink-0 mt-0.5">✗</span>
                  {con}
                </li>
              ))}
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>

        <a
          href={product.affiliateUrl}
          target="_blank"
          rel="nofollow noopener"
          class="inline-block border border-green-700 text-green-700 px-5 py-2.5 rounded-lg font-semibold text-sm hover:bg-green-700 hover:text-white transition-colors"
        >
          Buy {product.name} on Amazon →
        </a>
      </section>
    ))}

    <!-- Buying Guide -->
    <section class="border-t border-gray-100 pt-10 mb-16">
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mb-6">Smart Smoke Detector Buying Guide</h2>
      <div class="space-y-6 text-gray-700">
        <div>
          <h3 class="font-bold text-gray-900 mb-2">How many detectors does a typical home need?</h3>
          <p class="text-sm leading-relaxed">The NFPA 72 standard requires a smoke alarm on every level of the home (including the basement), inside every bedroom, and outside every sleeping area. For a 3-bedroom, 2-story home: at minimum 6 detectors. Adding CO detection to each location adds a meaningful layer of safety since CO enters sleeping areas from floors below. A full Nest Protect setup for a 3-bedroom home at 6 units × $119 = $714. For a budget-conscious home, use Kidde Smart units and add 1–2 Nest Protects in the sleeping areas where the verbal alert is most valuable.</p>
        </div>
        <div>
          <h3 class="font-bold text-gray-900 mb-2">Interconnect: why it matters</h3>
          <p class="text-sm leading-relaxed">When smoke detectors are interconnected, all units alarm when any one unit detects smoke or CO. This is critical in multi-story homes — a fire starting in the basement at 3am needs to wake you in your upstairs bedroom. All three picks support wireless interconnect within their own brands. Nest Protect units alert each other via Wi-Fi through the Nest app. Both Kidde picks (hardwired and battery) use Kidde's wireless interconnect protocol. Note: you cannot mix brands for interconnect — all units in a home should be from the same manufacturer for wireless interconnect to work.</p>
        </div>
        <div>
          <h3 class="font-bold text-gray-900 mb-2">What to do about nuisance alarms from cooking</h3>
          <p class="text-sm leading-relaxed">The most common smart smoke detector complaint is nuisance alarms triggered by cooking steam or smoke. Nest Protect's Heads-Up warning gives you a yellow light and verbal caution before the full alarm — wave your hand to silence it if you know it's harmless. All three detectors also allow silencing from the app. For kitchens specifically: mount the detector in an adjacent area (hallway near the kitchen, not directly above the stove), and choose photoelectric technology — it's less sensitive to cooking particles than ionization technology.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- FAQ -->
    <section class="border-t border-gray-100 pt-10 mb-16">
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mb-6">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
      <div class="space-y-6">
        <div>
          <h3 class="font-semibold text-gray-900 mb-2">What's the difference between photoelectric and ionization smoke detectors?</h3>
          <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 leading-relaxed">Ionization detectors respond faster to fast-flaming fires. Photoelectric detectors respond faster to slow, smoldering fires. All three picks on this page use photoelectric sensors, which the USFA recommends for primary bedroom and living area placement because smoldering fires are more common in home settings and give occupants more time to escape. Some experts recommend dual-sensor detectors — check each product's specifications if this distinction matters to you.</p>
        </div>
        <div>
          <h3 class="font-semibold text-gray-900 mb-2">Can I use Nest Protect with Alexa or Apple HomeKit?</h3>
          <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 leading-relaxed">Nest Protect works natively with Google Home and the Nest app. It does not natively support Apple HomeKit or Amazon Alexa direct integration. You can indirectly connect via Google Home's Alexa skill (for voice status checks) but it's not full integration. If Alexa or Google Home integration is important, either Kidde pick works well. Neither Kidde model supports Apple HomeKit — for HomeKit, Nest Protect is your only option in this guide.</p>
        </div>
        <div>
          <h3 class="font-semibold text-gray-900 mb-2">How do I know when to replace a smoke detector?</h3>
          <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 leading-relaxed">The NFPA recommends replacing smoke detectors every 10 years regardless of apparent function. The sensor itself degrades over time and becomes less responsive. The Kidde Smart's 10-year sealed battery makes replacement timing simple — when the battery ends, replace the unit. For Nest Protect and First Alert Onelink, set a calendar reminder for 10 years from installation date.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Related Guides -->
    <section class="border-t border-gray-100 pt-10">
      <h2 class="text-xl font-bold text-gray-900 mb-4">Related Guides</h2>
      <div class="grid sm:grid-cols-2 gap-4">
        <a href="/smart-home/best-smart-home-devices-for-elderly-parents" class="group block border border-gray-100 rounded-xl p-4 hover:border-green-200 hover:shadow-sm transition-all">
          <p class="text-xs text-green-700 font-semibold uppercase tracking-widest mb-1">Smart Home</p>
          <p class="font-medium text-gray-900 text-sm group-hover:text-green-700 transition-colors">Best Smart Home Devices for Elderly Parents →</p>
        </a>
        <a href="/smart-home/best-smart-home-starter-kit-under-200" class="group block border border-gray-100 rounded-xl p-4 hover:border-green-200 hover:shadow-sm transition-all">
          <p class="text-xs text-green-700 font-semibold uppercase tracking-widest mb-1">Smart Home</p>
          <p class="font-medium text-gray-900 text-sm group-hover:text-green-700 transition-colors">Best Smart Home Starter Kit Under $200 →</p>
        </a>
      </div>
    </section>

  </article>
</Layout>
